With the above figure we can conclude that there is a mix of distribution in this data, statistically speaking, there are many attributes like, jitter DDP, etc which are right skew-ed in the distribution with outliers. Although this does not matter when we use decision tree, there are few attributes that has normalized data. Also, by oberving the status attribute we can see that there around 50 people in this data who are healty rest all are affected by this disease.

#creating test data 

X=data.drop(['name','status'],axis=1)
Y=data['status']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.30)
print(X_train.shape)
print(X_test.shape)
print(y_train.shape)
print(y_test.shape)

In [84]:
#RandomForestClassifier to predict the status

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
rf=RandomForestClassifier()
rf.fit(X_train,y_train)
pred = rf.predict(X_test)
pred_train=rf.predict(X_train)
print(accuracy_score(y_test,pred))
print(accuracy_score(y_train,pred_train))

0.9491525423728814
1.0

Random Forest classifier has given the better among the above mentioned algos. This is because the ensemble technique is the better than the decision tree algorithm as it creates decision trees on the given data sets and then predicts for the solution on status, here.
